-- Italian Stocks: A2A, Bulgari, Buzzi, Pop. Milano, RCS, UniCredit
-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 2010-12-10T17:08:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-10/banco-popolare-enel-generali-pirelli-may-move-italy-equity-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
declined 46.22, or 0.2 percent, to 20,487.34 at the 5:30 p.m.
close in Milan. The gauge advanced 1.8 percent this week, the
biggest gain since October.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  A2A SpA  (A2A IM) rose for a fifth day, gaining 3.3 percent
to 1.08 euros. Equita Sim SpA removed Italy’s biggest municipal
utility from its “least preferred portfolio.”  Banca Popolare di Milano Scrl  (PMI IM) slid 1.7 percent to
2.87 euros, as a gauge for European banks ended three days of
gains, the longest winning streak since July.  Banco Popolare SC 
(BP IM) retreated 1.3 percent to 3.52 euros.  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA 
(ISP IM) and  UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM), Italy’s biggest banks,
dropped 1.6 percent to 2.17 euros and 1.6 percent to 1.70 euro,
respectively.  Bulgari SpA  (BUL IM) jumped 4 percent to 7.96 euros, the
biggest gain since Nov. 15. The shares of the world’s third-
largest jeweler climbed on “renewed speculation regarding a
potential use of cash by PPR SA after the French company agreed
to sell its Conforama chain,”  Gian Paolo Rivano , a fund manager
at Gesti-Re SGR SpA in Milan, said.  Buzzi Unicem SpA  (BZU IM) snapped a three-day gain, losing
1.8 percent to 8.29 euros. Italy’s second-biggest cement maker
said it wrote down the value of its Oglesby, Illinois cement
plant by 99.6 million euros ($131.9 million).  DiaSorin SpA  (DIA IM) rose 3.7 percent to 33.03 euros, the
highest price in three weeks. CA Cheuvreux upgraded the supplier
of diagnostics tests to “selected list” from “outperform”
and added the stock to its list of European health-care industry
top picks.  Lottomatica SpA  (LTO IM) increased 1.3 percent to 9.51
euros. Intermonte Sim SpA reiterated an “outperform” rating on
the lottery company, while trimming its price estimate to 13
euros from 15 euros, saying in a note that the “announcement of
debt refinancing is hitting the stock’s performance.”  The brokerage said that “current market prices factor in
an excessively negative scenario.”  RCS MediaGroup SpA  (RCS IM) advanced 6.4 percent to 1.08
euros, the biggest gain in six months. Mediobanca Securities
reiterated an “outperform” rating on the publisher of Italy’s
largest daily newspaper and lifted its price estimate by 3
percent to 1.52 euros, as “the three-year business plan,” due
on Dec. 17, “coupled with news related to the reorganization of
the portfolio assets should offer upside to the stock.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Francesca Cinelli  in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 